{{notability|biographies|date=October 2017}} {{Infobox artist | name = Lynda Grose | image = | caption = | birth_date = | death_date = | movement = | awards = | website = | field = Sustainable Fashion/Design | training = [[Kingston University]], London, UK }}
'''Lynda Grose''' is a designer in fashion and sustainability, educator, and consultant known for her pioneering work in [[sustainable fashion]] design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.textileartscouncil.org/fashion-and-sustainability/|title=Fashion and Sustainability: Design for Change|last=|first=|date=|website=Textile Arts Council|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
==Career== In 1990 Grose co-founded [[Esprit Holdings|Esprit]]’s ecollection division, a five-year research and development project marketed in 13 countries, which is cited "as the first ecologically responsible clothing line developed by a major corporation" and in doing so, Grose "set pioneering standards for the textile industry".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.textileartscouncil.org/fashion-and-sustainability/|title=Sustainable Design {{!}} Textile Arts Council, Fine Arts Museum of San Francisco|website=www.textileartscouncil.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref> Her Ecollection was founded in response to Esprit's company-wide focus on environmental awareness, begun by [[Esprit Holdings|Esprit]] co-founder [[Douglas Tompkins|Doug Tompkins]]. Grose's project began by researching the environmental impact of making Esprit clothing - from growing fibers, to dyeing, manufacturing and garment finishing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/04/13/news/patterns-070193.html|title=Patterns|last=SPINDLER|first=AMY M.|date=April 13, 1993|work=New York Times|access-date=15 March 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> The Ecollection used organic cotton, and less toxic dyes as a first step. Grose also began contracting with crafts cooperatives to hand-knit sweaters and make buttons and jewelry from tagua nuts. Grose believed that community development and fair treatment of textile workers was as important a part of the project as using more sustainable materials.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moed|first=Andrea|date=October 1994|title=Dress versus excess|url=|journal=Metropolis|volume=14|pages=73–78|via=}}</ref>
Grose is Professor and Chair of the Fashion Design program at [[California College of the Arts]]. She is a founding member of The Center for Sustainable Design, Surrey, England,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cfsd.org.uk/|title=Sustainable Innovation, Sustainable Design, Eco-innovation {{!}} The Centre for Sustainable Design|website=cfsd.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref> and the International Society for Sustainable Design,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isecoeco.org/tag/centre-for-sustainable-design/|title=Centre for Sustainable Design {{!}} The International Society for Ecological Economics|website=www.isecoeco.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref> and the Sustainable Cotton Project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sustainablecotton.org/pages/show/about-us|title=Sustainable Cotton Project {{!}} ABOUT US|website=www.sustainablecotton.org|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/academics/faculty/lgrose|title=Lynda Grose {{!}} California College of the Arts|website=www.cca.edu|access-date=2017-03-28}}</ref>
==Work== Lynda Grose co-authored with Dr. Kate Fletcher the book ''Fashion and Sustainability Design for Change''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laurenceking.com/en/fashion-sustainability-design-for-change/|title=Fashion & Sustainability: Design for Change|website=www.laurenceking.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-28}}</ref> She has published in journals and magazines and has contributed to 'Opening up the Wardrobe: a methods book' (Novus), 'Fashion Fibers: Designing for Sustainability', (Bloomsbury), 'The Routledge Handbook on Sustainable Fashion'' (Routledge), ''Sustainable Textiles: Life Cycle and Environmental Impact'' (Woodhouse Publishing, London), and ''Sustainability in Fashion and Textiles: Values, Design, Production and Consumption'' (Greenleaf Publishing).
===Awards and nominations=== In 2007, she was listed on ''[[Grist (magazine)|Grist’s]]'' list of “15 Green Fashionistas".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://grist.org/article/fashionistas/|title=15 Green Fashionistas|date=2007-08-10|work=Grist|access-date=2017-03-16|language=en-US}}</ref>
